455
00:25:25.184 --> 00:25:27.744
We didn't get better responses combining it with our hypothesis.

456
00:25:28.104 --> 00:25:31.784
So what do you think is the hypothesis for what's driving the relapse when the

457
00:25:31.824 --> 00:25:35.604
antigen's still there, the antibodies still bind, and then we retreat with the same

458
00:25:35.624 --> 00:25:36.984
product and nothing happens?

459
00:25:37.184 --> 00:25:41.144
Yeah. Fantastic question. I actually talked to Al about the CD19 part just

460
00:25:41.164 --> 00:25:42.784
last week when we were at a conference together.

461
00:25:42.864 --> 00:25:45.784
So I was thinking of him when I said that. But, so I agree with you.

462
00:25:47.344 --> 00:25:51.284
If we're not losing BCMA, which again, 5% of patients will lose BCMA

463
00:25:51.324 --> 00:25:55.204
after CAR T, a little bit less than 5%, especially our patients who

464
00:25:55.224 --> 00:25:55.424
have

465
00:25:56.724 --> 00:26:00.624
TP53 17p deletion, because 16p is right next to it, and

466
00:26:00.644 --> 00:26:03.584
that's where BCMA is expressed. So there are some that lose it.

467
00:26:03.724 --> 00:26:07.544
But if patients get more than two, three years

468
00:26:07.604 --> 00:26:10.944
from their CARs, it looks like they do respond to

469
00:26:11.604 --> 00:26:12.864
BCMA CARs again. So,

470
00:26:13.784 --> 00:26:17.294
none of the trials-- Well, the trials allow for prior BCMA, some,

471
00:26:17.704 --> 00:26:21.664
so that DURGA study with CD19 BCMA, there's a small cohort that allowed

472
00:26:21.724 --> 00:26:23.404
that. None of the other trials did.

473
00:26:23.624 --> 00:26:27.064
And in the real world, insurance won't pay for two BCMAs.

474
00:26:27.344 --> 00:26:30.644
But when we've gotten it, because someone either changed insurance and they didn't

475
00:26:30.664 --> 00:26:34.384
know, or they were on a trial, and then we were able to get a commercial, it was

476
00:26:34.444 --> 00:26:36.724
100% response rate for that small group of patients.

477
00:26:36.764 --> 00:26:40.064
So if they get a certain amount of time, they do much better.

478
00:26:40.244 --> 00:26:44.144
It's if they relapse within that first year or so, that one

479
00:26:44.284 --> 00:26:47.224
with the same CAR T, we think there could be some antibodies.

480
00:26:47.284 --> 00:26:50.944
Again, no one's been able to prove it, but a different CAR T actually does work

481
00:26:50.984 --> 00:26:52.784
when the same one on the trials didn't.

482
00:26:53.924 --> 00:26:57.054
But we just don't have enough data to really say, "Could I treat again?

483
00:26:57.104 --> 00:27:00.324
If someone gets five years, can I treat again, and is it going to work?" It

484
00:27:00.344 --> 00:27:03.154
might. So I think with BCMA, it's a little tricky.

485
00:27:03.244 --> 00:27:06.524
Now, if you do bispecifics for a long time, we do see

486
00:27:06.564 --> 00:27:09.744
mutations. And then you have to know if that ScFv or that

487
00:27:10.424 --> 00:27:13.684
DDOM, whatever you're going to use, is going to attach that mutated BCMA.

488
00:27:14.224 --> 00:27:15.884
And again, we don't have any data on that.

489
00:27:15.894 --> 00:27:19.484
So I think there's a few different ways that patients might not respond,

490
00:27:19.964 --> 00:27:23.374
but there's just not as much data that shows that patients do respond if we get

491
00:27:23.404 --> 00:27:24.484
them in that right scenario.

492
00:27:26.704 --> 00:27:30.444
Yeah. Hi. Great presentation. In terms of thinking about

493
00:27:30.484 --> 00:27:34.164
T-cell engagers, can you comment on T-cell engagers prior to

494
00:27:34.204 --> 00:27:35.964
CAR and how you think about sequencing?

495
00:27:36.204 --> 00:27:37.624
Yeah, no. Great question and

496
00:27:38.504 --> 00:27:40.344
our biggest dilemma right now in myeloma.

497
00:27:41.004 --> 00:27:41.204
So,

498
00:27:42.084 --> 00:27:46.014
I think, and I will say Penn, Al Garfall actually gave

499
00:27:46.014 --> 00:27:49.764
a great discussion on maybe when we're doing bispecifics

500
00:27:49.824 --> 00:27:52.984
early line, that will change things.

501
00:27:53.044 --> 00:27:56.594
Most of our data's from late line. So these patients, they'll get a year from their

502
00:27:56.644 --> 00:27:58.764
bispecifics, and then we're trying to go to CAR.

503
00:27:58.844 --> 00:28:00.784
They've already had all this therapy.

504
00:28:00.844 --> 00:28:04.784
Just the logistics of trying to get their CAR made becomes a big deal.

505
00:28:04.924 --> 00:28:08.664
So we can't actually-- There's a lot of manufacturing

506
00:28:08.704 --> 00:28:10.744
fails because they've just had so much therapy.

507
00:28:10.864 --> 00:28:13.664
Now they've been on a T-cell engager this entire year, and then you're trying to

508
00:28:13.704 --> 00:28:16.104
make CARs, right? We're setting it up to fail.

509
00:28:16.744 --> 00:28:20.564
Early line, now that we have the MajesTEC-3 data, we have Techdara

510
00:28:20.644 --> 00:28:23.604
up front. What are we going to do because a lot of patients are going to get this

511
00:28:23.744 --> 00:28:25.344
in the community where they can't get CAR.

512
00:28:26.144 --> 00:28:29.604
I'm hoping that what we'll be able to show is fixed duration Tech

513
00:28:30.064 --> 00:28:33.564
or Elra or any of our bi-- Lynvo, all of our bispecifics.

514
00:28:34.164 --> 00:28:37.784
I'm hoping that fixed duration can show that we can take patients off

515
00:28:37.824 --> 00:28:41.744
therapy, so that way, when they do relapse, hopefully it's been a few, maybe

516
00:28:41.804 --> 00:28:45.764
years, and then we can actually-- Those T-cells are better, as well as maybe

517
00:28:45.924 --> 00:28:48.124
we won't have the mutations in that BCMA.

518
00:28:48.584 --> 00:28:52.464
The big unknown is the mutation, the BCMA mutations that I worry about

519
00:28:52.504 --> 00:28:56.284
if people are on a bispecific or even an ADC for a really long time.

520
00:28:56.944 --> 00:29:00.564
I worry we're trying to cause resistance for CAR.

521
00:29:00.644 --> 00:29:04.464
So as of today, I still give CAR first because I have

522
00:29:04.544 --> 00:29:08.334
access to everything. It doesn't mean you shouldn't do a bispecific if a

523
00:29:08.364 --> 00:29:11.804
patient can't get to a CAR because it's amazing data.

524
00:29:11.824 --> 00:29:15.344
But I'm hoping that the bispecific world, we're going to start doing fixed duration

525
00:29:15.384 --> 00:29:19.344
instead, and then the sequencing won't be as big of an issue.

526
00:29:20.504 --> 00:29:24.364
And if I do use a bispecific first, I try to go for the GPRC5D

527
00:29:24.444 --> 00:29:24.544
one,

528
00:29:25.564 --> 00:29:27.784
just to make sure I have BCMA still there.

529
00:29:29.184 --> 00:29:31.884
All right. Let's give Dr. Patel another round of applause.

530
00:29:33.374 --> 00:29:40.633
Thank

531
00:29:40.633 --> 00:29:41.004
you.

532
00:29:43.144 --> 00:29:45.864
Can you help me? Oh, F star. Let's see. All right.

533
00:29:46.684 --> 00:29:50.224
Good. So our next speaker is Dr. Matt

534
00:29:50.284 --> 00:29:54.024
Frank. He's an assistant professor of medicine in the Division of

535
00:29:54.164 --> 00:29:57.464
Blood and Marrow Transplantation and Cellular Therapy at Stanford

536
00:29:57.524 --> 00:29:58.264
University.

537
00:29:59.624 --> 00:30:03.564
He takes care of high-risk lymphoma patients and has

538
00:30:03.604 --> 00:30:06.824
a particular interest in CAR T-cell therapies beyond

539
00:30:06.844 --> 00:30:10.444
targeting CD19 and identifying

540
00:30:10.464 --> 00:30:13.664
predictors of relapse and toxicity post-CAR T

541
00:30:13.674 --> 00:30:15.884
treatments.

542
00:30:20.884 --> 00:30:24.104
Good morning, everyone. Thank you for coming at this early hour.

543
00:30:24.444 --> 00:30:27.144
I want to thank the organizers for the invitation to speak.

544
00:30:28.234 --> 00:30:31.744
So I was given this daunting task of trying to talk about all the emerging

545
00:30:31.784 --> 00:30:34.604
approaches in both leukemia and lymphoma for CAR.

546
00:30:34.624 --> 00:30:38.524
So I apologize to those who are working on things that I couldn't include.

547
00:30:38.744 --> 00:30:42.424
But I've tried to create a slide set that includes as many things as possible.

548
00:30:42.944 --> 00:30:43.824
Here are my disclosures.

549
00:30:45.464 --> 00:30:47.264
I always want to just take stock of where we're at.

550
00:30:48.684 --> 00:30:52.184
This is an impressive list. This is a lot of patients who volunteer for clinical

551
00:30:52.244 --> 00:30:56.044
trials. We have many, many now FDA-approved

552
00:30:56.164 --> 00:30:59.784
options. We've heard about the two options in myeloma from Dr.

553
00:30:59.944 --> 00:31:01.624
Patel. Phenomenal talk, so thank you.

554
00:31:02.664 --> 00:31:04.784
But we also now have some newer approvals.

555
00:31:04.844 --> 00:31:08.804
So as of December of last year, we now have a lyso cell now

556
00:31:08.824 --> 00:31:10.364
approved for marginal zone lymphoma.

557
00:31:11.304 --> 00:31:13.324
So this is an impressive list.

558
00:31:14.624 --> 00:31:18.464
This dates back to 2017, so we've come a long, long way.

559
00:31:20.284 --> 00:31:24.044
But we also know that there are reasons that CAR T-cells fail, and I'm going to

560
00:31:24.104 --> 00:31:27.023
start with lymphoma. And so, we can see

561
00:31:27.084 --> 00:31:30.924
durable CR rates, depending if it's third

562
00:31:30.984 --> 00:31:32.984
line or second line or first line,

563
00:31:33.964 --> 00:31:37.394
between 30% to 50%. In front line, it can be as high as

564
00:31:37.584 --> 00:31:41.544
70%.But we know that after you relapse,

565
00:31:41.584 --> 00:31:45.514
your outcomes are poor. So this is data from one of many

566
00:31:45.524 --> 00:31:49.234
groups who publish now in this space that after you've progressed with large cell

567
00:31:49.264 --> 00:31:49.864
lymphoma,

568
00:31:50.784 --> 00:31:52.644
your median survival is under six months.

569
00:31:53.564 --> 00:31:57.244
Now, with bispecifics, that might be a little bit longer, but it's not a full year

570
00:31:57.304 --> 00:31:59.864
yet. We're talking about very dismal outcomes.

571
00:32:00.934 --> 00:32:04.904
And one of the reasons that patients relapse is CD19 is lost

572
00:32:04.944 --> 00:32:06.824
or decreased or in some cases mutated.

573
00:32:07.404 --> 00:32:09.174
So here's an example that we had at Stanford.

574
00:32:09.894 --> 00:32:12.784
You can clearly see that they had a wonderful response, but now the disease is

575
00:32:12.804 --> 00:32:14.744
roaring back with no CD19 expression.

576
00:32:15.764 --> 00:32:19.624
So target something else. Pretty obvious, but it's actually a bit more

577
00:32:19.664 --> 00:32:23.244
complicated. So these are just a few of the

578
00:32:23.304 --> 00:32:25.924
targets that have been attempted in lymphoma.

579
00:32:25.934 --> 00:32:29.644
And we have certainly two approvals now that have these

580
00:32:29.684 --> 00:32:32.884
two different construct designs that target CD19.

581
00:32:33.504 --> 00:32:36.533
But now we are starting to have other designs that are being heavily tested, both

582
00:32:36.564 --> 00:32:39.564
the tandem bispecific and the bispecific bicistronic.

583
00:32:40.104 --> 00:32:43.383
Both of these now target CD19, CD20. I'll show you that data in a moment.

584
00:32:44.024 --> 00:32:47.644
But there are groups who have developed a trispecific tricistronic or a tandem

585
00:32:47.684 --> 00:32:50.764
trispecific or a trispecific bicistronic.

586
00:32:50.784 --> 00:32:54.404
And these are fun words to say, but it's basically just designing different

587
00:32:54.464 --> 00:32:58.424
ways of targeting different antigens and then having signals transduced through

588
00:32:58.464 --> 00:32:59.944
various mechanisms.

589
00:33:00.884 --> 00:33:04.284
These are in the clinic. This is not, but the concept is here.

590
00:33:04.924 --> 00:33:06.824
We basically want to target multiple antigens

591
00:33:07.764 --> 00:33:08.944
or alternative antigens.

592
00:33:10.464 --> 00:33:13.214
So those are the three most common in lymphoma, but certainly there are others

593
00:33:13.244 --> 00:33:13.704
emerging.

594
00:33:14.664 --> 00:33:17.244
But it's not so simple. There have been some CAR T-cell crashes.

595
00:33:18.024 --> 00:33:21.484
So we saw an anti-CD20 that showed a lot of promise in indolent lymphoma.

596
00:33:21.544 --> 00:33:25.524
However, the trial's on hold. I think other things have emerged and it's not

597
00:33:25.564 --> 00:33:26.084
moving forward.

598
00:33:27.084 --> 00:33:31.054
I was heavily involved with a CD22 CAR that was developed by Cargo, and I can get

599
00:33:31.064 --> 00:33:34.744
into the details why it didn't go so well, but it had poor durable

600
00:33:34.764 --> 00:33:38.604
remissions and had high rates of IECHS and HLH-like

601
00:33:38.664 --> 00:33:41.724
toxicity that led to five patients passing away.

602
00:33:41.884 --> 00:33:43.644
So we had to halt that trial.

603
00:33:45.064 --> 00:33:48.944
There was a anti-ROR1 CAR that, again, another

604
00:33:48.984 --> 00:33:52.024
good target, but there was a death in the first six, and that trial has been on

605
00:33:52.064 --> 00:33:52.504
hold.

606
00:33:53.524 --> 00:33:57.204
And then CD37 is found on T cells, on B cells, but the

607
00:33:57.244 --> 00:34:01.224
trial at MGH was halted after we had severe hypocellular

608
00:34:01.284 --> 00:34:04.984
marrow after two of the first five patients were treated. So it's not so simple.

609
00:34:05.084 --> 00:34:07.604
You can't just switch to another antigen and just keep moving forward.

610
00:34:08.904 --> 00:34:12.444
But this strategy is still very much the

611
00:34:12.504 --> 00:34:14.404
forefront right now in the lymphoma space.

612
00:34:14.444 --> 00:34:18.104
And here are two different concepts of how to target.

613
00:34:18.165 --> 00:34:18.564
So this

614
00:34:19.464 --> 00:34:23.344
one on this side of the slide is a tandem design where

615
00:34:23.384 --> 00:34:26.283
you have CD19, CD20 with this tether between.

616
00:34:27.124 --> 00:34:30.265
So this is an example from Miltenyi's Zantacel.

617
00:34:31.265 --> 00:34:34.884
And we also have a bicistronic where you're co-expressing

618
00:34:34.984 --> 00:34:38.584
two different CARs, and they both can signal independent of each other.

619
00:34:39.194 --> 00:34:43.124
They essentially take the construct of axicel and then add

620
00:34:43.185 --> 00:34:47.104
this anti-CD20 with a 4-1BB postin, and both

621
00:34:47.185 --> 00:34:49.564
are expressed. And I'll show you that data now.

622
00:34:51.304 --> 00:34:55.284
So Zantacel has been tested in third line large B-cell lymphoma,

623
00:34:55.404 --> 00:34:58.944
and we see that the overall response rate in this high-risk group

624
00:34:58.954 --> 00:35:02.384
is 73% with a CR rate around half.

625
00:35:02.944 --> 00:35:06.424
The PFS is around nine months, but importantly, we see pretty minimal

626
00:35:06.464 --> 00:35:10.424
toxicity, about a 4% grade three ICANS and no grade three

627
00:35:10.544 --> 00:35:11.044
CRS.

628
00:35:11.844 --> 00:35:12.944
And it looks fairly durable.

629
00:35:13.904 --> 00:35:17.704
So this is looking like it's going to move toward hopefully approval at some point.

630
00:35:18.264 --> 00:35:20.424
But this is also now being tested in other areas.

631
00:35:20.724 --> 00:35:23.234
So CNS lymphoma, both primary and secondary.

632
00:35:24.044 --> 00:35:27.984
But the data from the Rav Shah group at Wisconsin has been pretty

633
00:35:28.004 --> 00:35:31.524
impressive. So this is the data for Zantacel in mantle cell lymphoma.

634
00:35:32.544 --> 00:35:34.064
These were fairly high-risk patients.

635
00:35:34.184 --> 00:35:36.904
There's only 17 of them, but it was still looking very promising.

636
00:35:37.124 --> 00:35:40.424
Almost half had TP53 aberrations.

637
00:35:41.104 --> 00:35:41.264
One in

638
00:35:42.244 --> 00:35:45.593
20% or so had complex karyotype. So overall, a very high-risk group.

639
00:35:46.364 --> 00:35:48.544
And we're seeing these very durable

640
00:35:49.584 --> 00:35:52.484
remissions. And you can see the PFS curve here.

641
00:35:52.584 --> 00:35:56.124
Also notably, the rates of grade three, four

642
00:35:56.223 --> 00:35:58.793
ICANS is fairly low compared to what we have.

643
00:35:59.824 --> 00:36:00.884
So we'll need long-term follow-up.

644
00:36:00.904 --> 00:36:04.224
There's a phase two trial enrolling now that's enrolling pretty quickly.

645
00:36:05.024 --> 00:36:08.984
And there's a question of whether or not this can go after frontline instead of we

646
00:36:09.044 --> 00:36:12.144
no longer do auto transplants pretty much in mantle cells.

647
00:36:12.184 --> 00:36:15.944
So can we consolidate using the same kind of concepts that we see in myeloma that

648
00:36:15.964 --> 00:36:19.904
we heard from Dr. Patel? So that's emerging now in mantle cell.

649
00:36:21.564 --> 00:36:23.014
So this is the Kite-363.

650
00:36:23.844 --> 00:36:25.824
Again, this is the bicistronic approach.

651
00:36:26.944 --> 00:36:30.264
They enrolled some very high-risk patients across three different dose levels.

652
00:36:30.404 --> 00:36:33.824
Dose level three was chosen for future development should it be

653
00:36:33.844 --> 00:36:34.824
developed.

654
00:36:35.724 --> 00:36:39.364
It's fairly standard. These are primary refractory or patients who've been

655
00:36:39.404 --> 00:36:42.504
through multiple lines. At dose level three,

656
00:36:44.464 --> 00:36:45.604
many patients required bridging.

657
00:36:45.944 --> 00:36:49.694
I'll note that the LDH was elevated, so it's a marker of more aggressive

658
00:36:49.744 --> 00:36:53.164
disease in about two-thirds of patients, which will be a

659
00:36:53.184 --> 00:36:56.784
distinguishing feature compared to other trials. It's a fairly high-risk group.

660
00:36:57.344 --> 00:37:00.784
And what they saw was a fairly high overall response rate of almost 90%.

661
00:37:01.424 --> 00:37:03.344
CR rates that almost approached 80%.

662
00:37:04.464 --> 00:37:07.724
This is in the CAR naive dose level three group.

663
00:37:08.464 --> 00:37:09.184
But importantly,

664
00:37:10.104 --> 00:37:14.044
we're seeing it's trending toward less neurotoxicity than we saw

665
00:37:14.144 --> 00:37:18.094
with axicel. So even though we've added a new CAR and using

666
00:37:18.104 --> 00:37:21.694
the same construct as axicel, because it's probably being triggered off a 4-1BB

667
00:37:22.004 --> 00:37:24.803
construct, we're seeing less neurotox. That's at least a thought.

668
00:37:26.124 --> 00:37:29.624
And so overall, this is looking promising, and the responses look durable.

669
00:37:29.634 --> 00:37:32.994
We're seeing a six-month durable CR rate of almost 72%.

670
00:37:33.504 --> 00:37:35.314
So this is encouraging, but it's small numbers.

671
00:37:35.384 --> 00:37:37.464
We're going to see if that holds up with more

672
00:37:37.504 --> 00:37:41.204
testing.There are also other groups.

673
00:37:41.264 --> 00:37:44.724
So this is a CAR from Johnson &amp; Johnson.

674
00:37:44.764 --> 00:37:48.104
So this is, again, a sort of a tandem bispecific.

675
00:37:48.344 --> 00:37:52.254
So it has a CD19 that's proximal to the signaling domain, and then

676
00:37:52.364 --> 00:37:56.334
an anti-CD20 that recognizes two non-contiguous regions of

677
00:37:56.364 --> 00:37:56.884
CD20.

678
00:37:57.804 --> 00:38:00.164
Again, there was some dose escalation, dose finding.

679
00:38:00.204 --> 00:38:03.074
They've picked 75 million CAR-positive cells to move forward with.

680
00:38:03.984 --> 00:38:07.754
Again, a fairly high-risk group. LDH was elevated in about

681
00:38:07.784 --> 00:38:10.944
one-third of patients. So overall, a pretty representative group.

682
00:38:12.084 --> 00:38:14.524
Here again, we see very high response rates,

683
00:38:15.384 --> 00:38:19.314
over 90%, approaching 100%. CR rates across all

684
00:38:19.344 --> 00:38:20.104
these different groups

685
00:38:20.964 --> 00:38:24.704
that were in the 75% to 80% range. So again, very

686
00:38:24.804 --> 00:38:28.044
encouraging by just adding that second target, you're starting to

687
00:38:28.104 --> 00:38:31.964
